to the Democratic party that has lasted to our own time. The last group to join the New Deal coalition, they have been the group that remained the most loyal to the Democratic party. This book explains the sources of their commitment in the 1930s. It stresses the central role of economic concerns in shaping black political behavior and clarifies both the New Deal record on race and the extraordinary relationship between black voters and the Roosevelts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aVotingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAfro-American.  aAlexander, Will W.  aBrown, Earl.  aChicago Defender.  aClark, Kenneth B.  aCrisis.  aDavis, John P.  aDepression, the.  aEarly, Stephen.  aFarley, James A.  aGuffey, Joseph F.  aHastie, William H.  aHill, T. Arnold.  aHopkins, Harry.  aHoward University.  aJohnson, James Weldon.  aJones, J. Raymond.  aKent, Frank R.  aKu Klux Klan (KKK).  aMcDuffie, Elizabeth.  aMcIntyre, Marvin.  aNational Youth Administration (NYA).  aNew York Amsterdam News.  aPittsburgh Courier.  aRobinson, Joseph T.  aRoosevelt, Sara Delano.  aantilynching legislation.  aelection of 1936.  alynchings.  apatronage.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691218007zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691218007423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691218007.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPA